JEurope WSJ Japanese Online WSJ-PRO-WSJ.com WSJSunday HOLY SEE POPE POPE BENEDICT POPE BENEDICT LETTER VATICAN VATICAN PRESS OFFICE SB126955385469309739639045841154602506946061 Benedict XVI Paul, Paul Pope Francis Viganò, Dario SYND CODES_REVIEWED Europe News </DescField><DescField fid="ipcns">OEUN </DescField></DescTPC></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">World</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Vatican Media Chief Quits Over Use of Letter From Retired Pope Benedict; Pope Francis chose Msgr. Dario Viganò in 2015 to overhaul the Holy See's media operation</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>ROME—The head of the Vatican communications office resigned over the promotional use of a letter from retired Pope Benedict XVI, an incident that has undermined the credibility of a media operation that is being reorganized under Pope Francis.</Para><Para>The pope chose Msgr. Dario Viganò in 2015 to oversee the merger of the Vatican's media outlets and modernize their operations. Msgr. Viganò's resignation stems from the publication last week of portions of a letter the monsignor had received <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/pope-benedict-protects-pope-francis-right-flank-1520960271?mod=searchresults&amp;page=1&amp;pos=1">from retired Pope Benedict</ELink> commenting on a new series of academic studies, published by the Vatican press, of Pope Francis' theological ideas.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>The retired pope's quoted comments, which were widely reported at the time, played down his differences with his more liberal successor and attested to an "interior continuity between the two pontificates, notwithstanding all the differences in style and temperament."</Para><Para>But later in the week, it was reported that a photograph of the letter distributed to journalists had been altered to blur lines in which Pope Benedict stated that he was too busy to read or comment substantially on the books in question.</Para><Para>That revelation was especially embarrassing less than two months after <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/pope-says-fake-news-is-devils-work-1516797410">Pope Francis denounced "fake news"</ELink> as the divisive work of the devil and called on journalists to observe accuracy in their reporting.</Para><Para>On Saturday, the Vatican published Pope Benedict's entire letter, including a section in which he criticized the Vatican for including among the authors of the book series a German theologian who he said had "virulently" attacked his teaching and that of his predecessor, St. John Paul II, particularly on questions of moral doctrine.</Para><Para>The reference to the German theologian pointed to Pope Francis' most controversial difference with his predecessor—his approach to moral theology. Pope Francis has raised concerns among conservatives with his more liberal statements on sexual and medical ethics, and <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/pope-francis-calls-for-leniency-toward-divorced-catholics-1460109702">his call for greater leniency</ELink> toward divorced Catholics who remarry without an annulment of the first marriage.</Para><Para>The controversy over Pope Benedict's letter largely obscured celebrations of the fifth anniversary of Pope Francis' election on March 13 and his inauguration as pope on March 19.</Para><Para>In his March 19 resignation letter to the pope, Msgr. Viganò asked to step down lest his continued presence "in any way delay, damage or indeed block" changes under way in the media operation. He didn't immediately respond to a request for additional comment.</Para><Para>In his letter Wednesday accepting Msgr. Viganò's resignation, Pope Francis praised him for "great commitment" and humility, and asked him to remain as an adviser to his yet-to-be-named successor.</Para><Para>Write to Francis X. Rocca at <ELink type="webpage" ref="mailto:francis.rocca@wsj.com">francis.rocca@wsj.com</ELink></Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">By Francis X. Rocca </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">Copyright 2018 Dow Jones &amp; Company, Inc. All Rights Reserved. </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item><Item subtype="primary" size="0" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/vatican-media-chief-quits-over-use-of-letter-from-retired-pope-benedict-1521651472" type="webpage"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

